I think what you are looking for is [ffi.Callback()][1] which basically returns a pointer that can be passed to a C function:
solution for your problem would look like something like this (example.js):

    const intPin = 40;
    const state = 0;
    const lib = require(&#39;./c_functions&#39;);
     
    const abc = () =&gt; {
        console.log(&quot;state: &quot;,state);
        state++;
    }

    const pointerToMyFunction = ffi.Callback(&#39;void&#39;, [], abc);

    //now pass pointer of abc() to attachInterrupt function
    lib.c_functions.attachInterrupt(intPin,pointerToMyFunction);

`ffi.Callback` accepts return type, argument types and javascript function as parameters and return pointer to this function. I passed empty array as second parameter because `abc()` doesn&#39;t accept anything. you can see more examples in the link above.

(also try to use `const` and `let` instead of `var` :d)


  [1]: https://github.com/node-ffi/node-ffi/wiki/Node-FFI-Tutorial

